Or try this (a real-world case):

I&#39;m editing a field in my form, and something happens asynchronously 
such that the action of editing a field in the form is no longer valid.  
There are several options of what to do at the interface level (with 
varying degrees of UI acceptableness and programmatic complexity), but 
your mediator knows nothing of the editor, nor of how it relates to the 
form, or of any other transient objects that may be introduced (dialogs, 
swapped-out panes) in order to rectify the situation.

The programmatic easy-to-test solution may not be the one required for 
usability of the UI.

On Tuesday, June 11, 2002, at 09:59 AM, Luca Sfarzo wrote:

&gt; Hi think that using a mediator could guarantee you from separating the
&gt; mechanism for handling data that lies deep in the &quot;core&quot; of your 
&gt; application
&gt; from the GUI details, but sometimes the behavior of a single form can be
&gt; driven by a many-state state machine (so being very complex) and some
&gt; transitions should rely on some other data liyng somewhere else in the 
&gt; depth
&gt; of the application.
&gt; Here the problem arises.
&gt;
&gt; One example should be if I would test my GUI behavior when something
&gt; somewhere else changes.
&gt;
&gt; I.e. I&#39;m editing some fields to be sent later to a server and the 
&gt; connection
&gt; goes down. Ok the mediator can do the great part of the job but what if 
&gt; my
&gt; current form should let me save the data into a file in order to 
&gt; retrieve
&gt; them later? That kind of knowledge lies inside the form (it&#39;s its own
&gt; responsibility, above all!) while the constraints come from the outer 
&gt; world.
